SIMPLE: laughter
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Laughter
<hw>Laugh"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>hleahtor</ets>; akin to OHG. <ets>hlahtar</ets>, G.
<ets>gel⟦aum⟧chter</ets>, Icel. <ets>hl⟦amac⟧tr</ets>, Dan.
<ets>latter</ets>. See <er>Laugh</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos> ]</ety> <def>A
movement (usually involuntary) of the muscles of the face, particularly
of the lips, with a peculiar expression of the eyes, indicating
merriment, satisfaction, or derision, and usually attended by a sonorous
and interrupted expulsion of air from the lungs. See <er>Laugh</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The act of <qex>laughter</qex>, which is a sweet contraction of
the muscles of the face, and a pleasant agitation of the vocal organs,
is not merely, or totally within the jurisdiction of ourselves.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Archly the maiden smiled, and with eyes overrunning with
<qex>laughter</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Laughterless</ent>⟦br⟧
